<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-272-040  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 272 040.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 16 1989 v3 n20 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Apple unlocks Communications Toolbox. (introduces the MacintoshCommunications Toolbox) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Brower, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Macintosh Communications Toolbox (Program development software)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionProgram Development ToolsCommunications Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Apple unlocks Communications ToolboxandM;San Jose, Calif.andP;  -- Apple wants to take the black art out oftelecommunications and replace it with the Macintosh interface.andM;At this week's developers' conference the company introduced the MacintoshCommunications Toolbox, a new set of tools programmers can use to maketelecommunications &quot;intuitive&quot; for Mac users.andP;  Its developers hope that theirsoftware will standardize the Mac's user interface for communications.andM;The toolbox, which will be part of the upcoming System 7.0, includes managersfor connections, terminal emulaiton and file transfers.andP;  The managers controlapplication-level access to tools residing in the System folder.andM;System 7.0 will ship with modem and serial connection tools and threeterminal emulation tools for TTY, VT100 and VT320 emulation, as well as toolsfor text-only and Xmodem file transfers.andP;  The toolbox will also eventuallyinclude an LAT tool, providing access to Digital Equipment Corp.'s Local AreaTransport technology (see related story, Page 5).andM;However, users will only have access to those tools through applications, andthat may take quite a while.andP;  Although Apple said it has sent pre-releaseversion of the toolbox to &quot;select developers,&quot; many developers said last weekthat they had received only documentation.andP;  &quot;Developers need to have thesoftware for six months at least before the toolbox starts doing anything forthe average user,&quot; said Frank Slaughter, vice president of engineering forShiva Corp. of Cambridge, Mass.andM;The toolbox, he said, will facilitate mainframe links and provide a standardway to make use of additional serial ports.andM;In additional, the toolbox opens communications to developers ofnon-telecommunications applications.andP;  Word processors written to talk to theCommunications Toolbox, fox example, would have access to any of the tools ina userhs system folder.andP;  This would allow users to send documents directly toa service bureau, for instance.andM;Advanced Apple networking software, such as its MacX25 and MacPAD tools (seestory, Page 1) will be based on the new Communications Toolbox.andO;</TEXT></DOC>